  "prompt": "What are the fundamental rights in Russia?",
  "response": "In Russia, fundamental rights are primarily outlined in Chapter 2 of the Russian Constitution, which was adopted in 1993. Some key fundamental rights include:\n\n1. Right to Life\n- Prohibition of death penalty\n- Protection of human life and dignity\n\n2. Personal Rights\n- Right to freedom and personal inviolability\n- Right to privacy\n- Freedom of movement\n- Freedom of conscience and religion\n\n3. Political Rights\n- Right to participate in elections\n- Freedom of assembly\n- Right to form public associations\n- Right to information\n\n4. Social and Economic Rights\n- Right to work\n- Right to social security\n- Right to healthcare\n- Right to education\n- Right to housing\n\n5. Equality Rights\n- Equality before the law\n- Prohibition of discrimination based on gender, race, nationality, language, origin, property status, and other factors\n\n6. Property Rights\n- Right to own property\n- Right to inherit\n- Freedom of economic activity\n\n7. Judicial Rights\n- Right to legal protection\n- Right to qualified legal assistance\n- Presumption of innocence\n- Protection from arbitrary arrest or prosecution\n\nWhile these rights are constitutionally guaranteed, international human rights organizations have often criticized Russia for limitations and inconsistent implementation of these rights in practice.",
